{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d8c0f6c8-f996-449c-8b91-0c6cd4fe68e7","content":"Here's what to do:\n\n1. **Remove** the `xunit.runner.visualstudio` package reference.\n\n2. **Add** these packages:\n   ```xml\n   <PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Platform\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n   <PackageReference Include=\"xunit.runner.microsofttestingplatform\" Version=\"1.*\" />\n   ```\n\n3. **Add** this property to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n4. **Enable** the generated entry point (MTP requires an executable):\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n     <GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>true</GenerateTestingPlatformEntryPoint>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\n5. **Run tests** with:\n   ```bash\n   dotnet test\n   ```\n   Or run the test project directly as an executable.\n\n**Key differences after migration:**\n- Your test assembly becomes an executable, not a library.\n- You can run it directly (`./MyTests`) with MTP's built-in CLI (`--list-tests`, `--filter`, etc.).\n- `dotnet test` still works thanks to `TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport`.\n\nNo changes to your test code (`[Fact]`, `[Theory]`, etc.) are needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2f35dd0c-4229-4eec-83a2-95a18ae07358","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to migrate their xUnit.net project from VSTest (using `xunit.runner.visualstudio`) to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP). Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of this migration path.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"7037:913B3:DC1DB8B:F24C8D9:69F2A769"},"id":"9ea4b4d6-9f91-4eef-97be-fbbda61f31c7","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:50:59.259Z","parentId":"b6de4d9e-7f13-4aa1-8578-f5eae764f8ce"}
